10.2 Termination for Default:

Regardless of any other rights or remedies available to either Party, whether at law or otherwise, either Party retains the right to terminate this Agreement should the other Party fail in its contractual obligations. Such termination becomes effective if:

(a) The non-defaulting Party issues a written notification detailing the default;
(b) A period of thirty (30) days elapses following the breaching Party's receipt of said notice, and during this time the breaching Party has not rectified the default;
(c) However, if conditions specified in Section 10.3 [ACSI Termination] are met, the provisions of that section apply differently: in case of Company's failure to adhere to the customer service standards outlined in Section 2.4 [Technical Standards; Customer Service] and Exhibit B, ACSI may only exercise its termination right if such failure is material and significant, provided that ACSI has duly notified Company about the non-compliance, and after a lapse of sixty (60) days from the date of the notice, the company remains in default.

In this revised clause, I've aimed to maintain the original meaning while slightly altering the tone. The obligation for ACSI to terminate an agreement due to Company's failure to meet customer service requirements has been shifted to a conditional right that can only be exercised under specific circumstances, making it less immediate and more dependent on materiality of the breach and timeframes for compliance.
